          "body": "Orthodox evangelical interpreters have long disagreed about the referent of this temple vision. Premillennialists (Scofield, Walvoord, Block in part) read chapters 40-48 as a literal future temple to be built during the millennial reign of Christ — the sacrifices functioning as memorials to the cross, much as the Mosaic sacrifices functioned as anticipations. Amillennialists and many Reformed interpreters (Keil, Fairbairn, Duguid) read the vision as an idealized, symbolic portrayal of the restored covenant community — the spiritual realities of the new covenant expressed in the architectural and liturgical idiom Ezekiel's audience could understand. Both views take the text with full seriousness. The present study observes what the chapter actually says and resists foreclosing the eschatological question. What is not disputed: the theological principle of 42:20 — the holy/profane distinction — is binding in every era, and the vision of a holy God dwelling among a holy people has been inaugurated in Christ (John 1:14; Rev. 21:22) and awaits final consummation."
