        "title": "The sacred chambers — where the holy and the common meet under regulation",
        "range": "42:1-12",
        "excerpt": "He brought me out into the outer court, the way toward the north; and he brought me to the chamber which was opposite the separate area and opposite the building toward the north.",
        "body": "The opening of the chapter resumes the guided tour that began at 40:1, but now moves to spaces that have not yet been described: the two sets of sacred chambers flanking the temple on its north and south sides. The guide brings Ezekiel first northward (42:1), then the corresponding south chambers are described in 42:10-12. The repeated phrase 'opposite the separate area' (*gizrah*, 42:1, 10, 13) is the spatial key: these chambers are positioned in the restricted zone between the inner court and the outer court — a liminal space of intermediate holiness.\n\nThe architectural description (vv. 1-9) is complex, but its outline is clear: a three-story building, one hundred cubits long and fifty cubits wide (42:2), with an inner walkway ten cubits wide in front of it (42:4), galleries running across the face of the upper stories (42:3, 5-6), and an outer wall fifty cubits long on the court side (42:7). The three-story structure with galleries (42:3-6) creates a distinctive setback: the upper chambers are smaller because the galleries consume floor space from below, requiring each successive story to step back from the ground. This is not poor planning; it is the consequence of the gallery design, which provided covered walkways for priestly movement between chambers.\n\nThe symmetry of north (42:1-9) and south (42:10-12) is deliberate. Verse 11 states it explicitly: the south chambers had 'the same length and width, and all their exits were both according to their arrangements and openings.' The bilateral symmetry around the central sanctuary axis reflects the same design principle visible throughout the temple vision — divine order expressed in balanced proportion. The temple is not the product of human aesthetic preference; it is the product of divine prescription (cf. 43:10-11).\n\nThe entrance to the north chambers was from the east (42:9); the south chambers had a corresponding eastern entrance (42:12). This means that priests approaching the holy chambers did so from the east, the direction of the returning glory (43:2). The architecture is theologically oriented: the same compass direction through which God approaches is the direction through which the priests approach their sacred duties.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Gizrah* (separate area, 42:1) designates the restricted courtyard adjacent to the sanctuary — the term appears only in Ezekiel 40-42 in the entire Hebrew Bible, suggesting it is technical architectural vocabulary for this specific vision. *Attuq* (galleries, 42:3, 5) is also unique to Ezekiel (40-42), and its precise architectural meaning remains debated; the LXX renders it as a kind of peristyle or colonnade. *Lishkah* (chamber) occurs thirteen times in this chapter — a frequency that mirrors the chapter's architectural focus."
