        "title": "The holy chambers interpreted — priests near to the LORD eat the most holy things",
        "range": "42:13-14",
        "excerpt": "The north chambers and the south chambers, which are opposite the separate area, they are the holy chambers where the priests who are near to the LORD shall eat the most holy things.",
        "body": "After twelve verses of architectural description, the angel speaks for the first time in this chapter (42:13) — and in two verses provides the interpretive key for everything measured. The chambers are not administrative offices or storage rooms; they are 'holy chambers' where specific sacred acts take place. The angel's explanation has three components: the identification of the priests, the act of eating, and the regulation of garments.\n\nThe priests are identified as those 'near to the LORD' — a phrase that, in the context of Ezekiel's temple vision, specifically designates the Zadokite priests (40:46; 44:15-16). The Zadokites are elevated above the other Levites in the new temple vision because, unlike the rest of the Levitical priesthood, they 'kept charge of My sanctuary when the sons of Israel went astray' (44:15). Their privileged access to the most holy things is a reward for maintained fidelity. The phrase 'near to the LORD' is relational and earned — proximity to God is not automatic but the result of sustained obedience to His standards.\n\nThe eating of the most holy offerings in the holy chambers is rooted in Levitical law. Leviticus 6:16 required the grain offering to be eaten 'without leaven in the court of the tent of meeting'; Leviticus 6:26 required the sin offering to be eaten 'in the court of the tent of meeting'; Leviticus 7:6 required the guilt offering to be eaten 'in a holy place.' The new temple vision does not abrogate these requirements — it provides a permanent, architecturally designated space for them. The three offerings named (grain, sin, guilt) are the three categories of 'most holy things' (*qodesh qodashim*) — the offerings that required the strictest ritual handling and the most restricted eating.\n\nThe garment regulation of 42:14 deserves close attention. Priests who have been in the sanctuary cannot simply walk out into the outer court. They must first 'lay there their garments in which they minister, for they are holy.' The logic is the logic of holiness contagion: objects touched by the holy become holy themselves (Lev. 6:27-28). Priestly garments worn in the presence of the Ark and the altar have been saturated with sanctity; to carry them into the common outer court risks collapsing the boundary between holy and profane that the entire temple is designed to maintain. D. I. Block (*The Book of Ezekiel, Chapters 25-48*, NICOT, 1998) rightly observes that the regulation 'protects the community from unintentional contamination of holy things.' The priest then puts on 'other garments' — common clothes — before approaching 'that which is for the people.' The double clothing requirement embodies the priest's dual identity: simultaneously a holy servant of God and a mediating servant of the people.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qodesh qodashim* (most holy things, 42:13) — the superlative construct, 'holy of holies,' the same construction used for the inner sanctuary. *Qarov* (near to the LORD, 42:13) — to draw near, approach; a cultic term for priestly access to the divine presence (cf. Num. 17:13; Ezek. 40:46). *Sharat* (minister, 42:14) — to serve, attend upon; always of priestly or levitical service in the sanctuary. *Beged* (garments, 42:14) — the same word used for the priestly vestments of Exodus 28-29."
